<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,455,267,293]" box="[189,455,267,293]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,455,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,455,267,293]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnostic comments</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1399,313,446]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
As mentioned above, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[465,590,314,339]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grisoni">
<emphasis box="[465,590,314,339]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">N. grisoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mayr" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[661,818,313,339]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulatus">
<emphasis box="[661,818,313,339]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">N. angulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are straightforwardly distinguishable from the remainder of the group. At the same time they are morphologically very close to each other and only separable on the basis of body colour. For a more in-depth discussion we refer to the species account of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mayr" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[189,339,419,445]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera" genus="Nesomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulatus">
<emphasis box="[189,339,419,445]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">N. angulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,284,484,510]" box="[189,284,484,510]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,284,484,510]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,284,484,510]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Biology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1398,531,592]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Very little information about the natural history of this species is available. It seems to live on vegetation in rain forest habitats.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1354,631,705]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,342,631,657]" box="[189,342,631,657]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
